---
import ArticleLayout from '../../../components/ArticleLayout.astro';

const sidebarItems = [
  {
    label: 'Feeding',
    href: '#feeding',
    children: [
      { label: 'Forbidden foods', href: '#forbidden-foods' },
      { label: 'Treats',          href: '#treats' },
    ],
  },
  { label: 'Litter',       href: '#litter' },
  { label: 'Environment',  href: '#environment' },
  { label: 'Hygiene',      href: '#hygiene' },
  {
    label: 'Health',
    href: '#health',
    children: [
      { label: 'Sterilization', href: '#sterilization' },
      { label: 'Parasites',     href: '#parasites' },
    ],
  },
  { label: 'Walks',        href: '#walks' },
  {
    label: 'Behaviour',
    href: '#behaviour',
    children: [
      { label: 'Play',       href: '#play' },
      { label: 'Alone time', href: '#alone' },
      { label: 'Changes',    href: '#changes' },
    ],
  },
];
---

<ArticleLayout
  lang="en"
  animal="cats"
  title="Cat care guide"
  sidebarItems={sidebarItems}
>

  <!-- ─── FEEDING ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section id="feeding" class="mb-14 scroll-mt-20">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-[#2d5a4e] dark:text-[#D37475] mb-3 pb-1 border-b border-[#e8c4b8]">1. Feeding</h2>

    <h3 class="font-bold text-xl text-[#774A33] dark:text-[#D49E84] mb-2">Diet basics</h3>
    <p>
      Cats are strict carnivores and need a diet rich in animal protein.
      That said, other components of the diet matter too and should not be neglected.
    </p>
    <p class="mt-2">
      Contrary to popular belief, cats should <strong>not</strong> eat wet food exclusively.
      Kibble is essential for dental health — wet food should only be a complement or treat.
      Cats often prefer wet food because of animal fat (very aromatic), but it usually
      contains little real meat, often of lower quality.
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-bold text-xl text-[#774A33] dark:text-[#D49E84] mt-5 mb-2">How to choose kibble</h3>
    <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-2 mt-1">
      <li>
        <strong>Meat ≥ 70 %</strong> — pay attention to the exact description.
        "Chicken" alone is vague and undesirable; "fresh deboned chicken" is far better.
        Cats can be allergic to certain proteins, so observe their reaction to any new food.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Carbohydrates matter.</strong> Poor sources (corn, wheat) can trigger allergies.
        Good sources: sweet potato, whole-grain rice, peas.
      </li>
      <li>
        A trustworthy manufacturer lists a <strong>detailed composition with percentages</strong>.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-[#555] dark:text-[#848484]">
      <em>Recommended brands — Premium:</em> Alleva, Acana, Applaws. &nbsp;
      <em>Good quality:</em> Carnilove, N&amp;D.
    </p>

    <div class="mt-5 mb-5 h-75 bg-white dark:bg-[#454341] border border-dashed border-[#e8c4b8] rounded-lg flex items-center justify-center text-[#7a9070] text-sm italic">
      <img class="w-110 dark:hidden" src="/ingridients-cats.png">
      <img class="w-90 hidden dark:block" src="/ingridients-cats-dark.png">
    </div>
    <p class="mt-2 text-xs text-[#7a9070] dark:text-[#A9AFA0]">
      Source:
      <a href="https://icatcare.org/advice/feeding-your-cat/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
         class="underline hover:text-[#2d5a4e]">International Cat Care — Feeding your cat</a>
    </p>

    <!-- FORBIDDEN FOODS -->
    <h3 id="forbidden-foods" class="font-bold text-xl text-[#774A33] dark:text-[#D49E84] mt-10 mb-2 scroll-mt-20">Forbidden foods</h3>
    <p>Many foods harmless to humans can be dangerous or even fatal for cats.</p>
    <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-2 mt-2">
      <li>
        <strong>Milk</strong> — as cats age, the enzyme needed to digest lactose decreases
        significantly; milk causes serious digestive problems in adult cats.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Bones</strong> — small fish bones can lodge in the throat;
        chicken bones lacerate the oesophagus and stomach, sometimes requiring emergency surgery.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Raw meat &amp; fish</strong> — risk of parasites, digestive disorders, and neurological problems.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <p class="mt-4 font-semibold text-[#8b2020] dark:text-[#944040]">Toxic to the liver:</p>
    <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-1 mt-1">
      <li>Grapes &amp; raisins</li>
      <li>Avocado</li>
      <li>Chocolate</li>
      <li>Onion &amp; garlic</li>
      <li>Very fatty or salty foods</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="mt-3 font-bold text-xl text-[#8b2020] dark:text-[#944040]">Alcohol can cause coma and death even in tiny amounts!</p>
    <p class="mt-2 text-sm italic">
      Before giving your cat any human food, ask yourself: could you call an emergency vet
      if things went wrong? Every minute counts.
    </p>

    <p class="mt-2 text-xs text-[#7a9070] dark:text-[#A9AFA0]">
      Source:
      <a href="https://www.aspca.org/pet-care/animal-poison-control/people-foods-avoid-feeding-your-pets"
         target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="underline hover:text-[#2d5a4e]">
        ASPCA — Foods to avoid feeding your pets
      </a>
    </p>

    <!-- TREATS -->
    <h3 id="treats" class="font-bold text-xl text-[#774A33] dark:text-[#D49E84] mt-10 mb-2 scroll-mt-20">Treats</h3>
    <p>
      Treats are important for positive reinforcement, but must be chosen carefully.
      They should represent only <strong>5–10 %</strong> of total daily intake.
    </p>
    <p class="mt-2">
      In summer, during heat waves, you can freeze wet food into small portions to help
      your cat cool down. Lick mats are another great option.
    </p>
    <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-2 mt-3">
      <li>
        <strong>Avoid popular mass-market brands</strong> (Whiskas, Sheba, Dreamies) —
        they invest in marketing, not quality. "Animal by-products" on the label often hides
        chemically treated scraps, skin and bone.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Simpler is better.</strong> Dried organ pieces (e.g. Wild Freedom) make
        excellent treats — the ingredient list is exactly what it says.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <div class="mt-5 h-60 bg-[#f5f0eb] dark:bg-[#454341] border border-dashed border-[#e8c4b8] rounded-lg flex items-center justify-center text-[#7a9070] text-sm italic">
      <img class="w-60" src="/treats.png">
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ─── LITTER ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section id="litter" class="mb-14 scroll-mt-20">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-[#2d5a4e] dark:text-[#D37475] mb-3 pb-1 border-b border-[#e8c4b8]">2. Litter</h2>
    <p>
      Cats are very demanding and sensitive. If anything displeases them — smell, texture,
      location — they will refuse to use the tray and go elsewhere.
      This is why you need <strong>at least two litter trays</strong>.
    </p>
    <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-[#555] dark:text-[#848484] italic">
      Example: a cat wants to go to the toilet, but someone used an air freshener nearby.
      The intense smell makes the cat feel uncomfortable or unable to recognise its tray —
      so it finds another spot.
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-bold text-xl text-[#774A33] dark:text-[#D49E84] mt-5 mb-2">Types of litter</h3>
    <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-2 mt-1">
      <li>
        <strong>Bentonite &amp; wood</strong> — most popular but often low quality.
        Bentonite produces a lot of dust (respiratory risk); wood litter can contain large splinters.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Silica</strong> — traps odours well, but the crunching sound frightens many
        cats, and granules can get stuck between paw pads — dangerous if swallowed.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Soy</strong> — natural, sometimes lightly scented, biodegradable.
        Less common; buy at pet shops or online.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <div class="mt-5 h-60 bg-[#f5f0eb] dark:bg-[#454341] border border-dashed border-[#e8c4b8] rounded-lg flex items-center justify-center text-[#7a9070] text-sm italic">
      <img class="w-80" src="/litter.png">
    </div>
    <p class="mt-2 text-xs text-[#7a9070] dark:text-[#A9AFA0]">
      Source:
      <a href="https://icatcare.org/advice/the-litter-tray/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
         class="underline hover:text-[#2d5a4e]">International Cat Care — The litter tray</a>
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- ─── ENVIRONMENT ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section id="environment" class="mb-14 scroll-mt-20">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-[#2d5a4e] dark:text-[#D37475] mb-3 pb-1 border-b border-[#e8c4b8]">3. Environment</h2>

    <h3 class="font-bold text-xl text-[#774A33] dark:text-[#D49E84] mb-2">Windows</h3>
    <p>
      Windows are responsible for the majority of cat injuries and deaths at home.
    </p>
    <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-2 mt-2">
      <li>
        <strong>Fully open windows</strong> — remember: <strong>cats fall out of windows.</strong>
        Even a calm cat that has never jumped can be startled by a bird, a sudden noise, or
        a passing car. The only safe solution is a purpose-made protective net.
        A standard fly screen will not support an adult cat's weight — and because it creates
        a false sense of security, cats push against it harder and fall.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Tilt-and-turn position</strong> — widely considered safe, but it is not.
        A cat trying to squeeze through the narrow gap can get its body trapped between the
        frames. This compresses organs and can cause permanent disability or death.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <div class="mt-5 h-60 bg-white dark:bg-[#454341] border border-dashed border-[#e8c4b8] rounded-lg flex items-center justify-center text-[#7a9070] text-sm italic">
      <img class="w-140" src="/window-safe.jpg">
    </div>

    <h3 class="font-bold text-xl text-[#774A33] dark:text-[#D49E84] mt-7 mb-2">Scratching post</h3>
    <p>
      Cats need to scratch to sharpen their claws, relieve stress, and mark their territory.
      Buy a scratching post and show your cat how to use it — this protects your furniture.
    </p>

    <p class="mt-4 text-xs text-[#7a9070] dark:text-[#A9AFA0]">
      Source:
      <a href="https://icatcare.org/advice/making-a-safe-home-for-your-cat/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
         class="underline hover:text-[#2d5a4e]">International Cat Care — Making a safe home</a>
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- ─── HYGIENE ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section id="hygiene" class="mb-14 scroll-mt-20">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-[#2d5a4e] dark:text-[#D37475] mb-3 pb-1 border-b border-[#e8c4b8]">4. Hygiene</h2>
    <p>
      Cats are extremely clean animals and groom themselves constantly — be very careful
      about anything applied to their coat, as they will ingest it.
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-bold text-xl text-[#774A33] dark:text-[#D49E84] mt-5 mb-2">Bathing</h3>
    <p>
      Cats have sensitive skin with a natural protective barrier disrupted by washing.
      <strong>Do not bathe your cat without necessity</strong> — for instance, only if they
      have come into contact with something toxic or dangerous to lick.
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-bold text-xl text-[#774A33] dark:text-[#D49E84] mt-5 mb-2">Claws</h3>
    <p>
      Even though cats sharpen their claws daily, regular trimming prevents problems.
      Use a purpose-made cat nail clipper — some have a stop guard to prevent cutting too far.
      <strong>Only cut the translucent tip;</strong> avoid the pink quick (blood vessels and nerves).
    </p>

    <p class="mt-2 text-xs text-[#7a9070] dark:text-[#A9AFA0]">
      Source:
      <a href="https://icatcare.org/advice/grooming-your-cat/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
         class="underline hover:text-[#2d5a4e]">International Cat Care — Grooming your cat</a>
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- ─── HEALTH ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section id="health" class="mb-14 scroll-mt-20">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-[#2d5a4e] dark:text-[#D37475] mb-3 pb-1 border-b border-[#e8c4b8]">5. Health</h2>
    <p>
      Even indoor cats need an <strong>annual vaccination</strong> and parasite treatment —
      viruses and parasites can travel indoors on shoe soles and clothing.
    </p>

    <h3 id="sterilization" class="font-bold text-xl text-[#774A33] dark:text-[#D49E84] mt-5 mb-2 scroll-mt-20">Sterilization</h3>
    <p>
      Sterilization is strongly recommended. It drastically reduces the risk of mammary
      tumours (<strong>90 % of which are malignant</strong> in cats) and completely eliminates
      ovarian and uterine diseases. Studies show sterilised females live on average
      <strong>39 % longer</strong>.
    </p>

    <p class="mt-2 text-xs text-[#7a9070] dark:text-[#A9AFA0]">
      Source:
      <a href="https://icatcare.org/advice/neutering-your-cat/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
         class="underline hover:text-[#2d5a4e]">International Cat Care — Neutering your cat</a>
    </p>

    <h3 id="parasites" class="font-bold text-xl text-[#774A33] dark:text-[#D49E84] mt-8 mb-2 scroll-mt-20">Parasite control &amp; vaccination schedule</h3>
    <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-2 mt-1">
      <li>Flea &amp; tick treatment + deworming — <strong>10 days before</strong> the annual booster.</li>
      <li>Annual booster vaccination at the vet.</li>
      <li>
        Parasite treatment can be done at home, but use
        <strong>vet-recommended products only</strong> —
        shampoos, collars and essential oils are ineffective.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p class="mt-3 text-xs text-[#7a9070] dark:text-[#A9AFA0]">
      Source:
      <a href="https://wsava.org/global-guidelines/vaccination-guidelines/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
         class="underline hover:text-[#2d5a4e]">WSAVA — Vaccination guidelines</a>
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- ─── WALKS ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section id="walks" class="mb-14 scroll-mt-20">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-[#2d5a4e] dark:text-[#D37475] mb-3 pb-1 border-b border-[#e8c4b8]">6. Walks</h2>
    <p>Cats can be walked outdoors, but preparation is key.</p>

    <h3 class="font-bold text-xl text-[#774A33] dark:text-[#D49E84] mt-5 mb-2">Equipment</h3>
    <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-2 mt-1">
      <li>
        <strong>Harness</strong> — always prefer a harness over a collar; much harder for
        the cat to wriggle out of.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Leash</strong> — standard length, not retractable (constant tension is
        uncomfortable for cats). <strong>Never let go of the leash</strong> — a frightened
        cat can bolt and climb somewhere dangerous or impossible to reach.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p class="mt-3">
      Vaccination and tick protection are <strong>mandatory</strong> before outdoor walks
      (see Health section).
    </p>

    <div class="mt-5 h-55 bg-[#f5f0eb] dark:bg-[#454341] border border-dashed border-[#e8c4b8] rounded-lg flex items-center justify-center text-[#7a9070] text-sm italic">
      <img class="w-60" src="/harness.png">
    </div>
    <p class="mt-2 text-xs text-[#7a9070] dark:text-[#A9AFA0]">
      Source:
      <a href="https://icatcare.org/advice/walking-your-cat-on-a-lead/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
         class="underline hover:text-[#2d5a4e]">International Cat Care — Walking your cat on a lead</a>
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- ─── BEHAVIOUR ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section id="behaviour" class="mb-14 scroll-mt-20">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-[#2d5a4e] dark:text-[#D37475] mb-3 pb-1 border-b border-[#e8c4b8]">7. Behaviour</h2>

    <h3 id="play" class="font-bold text-xl text-[#774A33] dark:text-[#D49E84] mb-2 scroll-mt-20">Play</h3>
    <p>
      Cats are hunters by nature and need to run, jump, and play. Even as they age and calm
      down, be prepared for midnight sprints around the apartment.
    </p>
    <h4 class="font-semibold mt-3 mb-1 text-[#2d5a4e] dark:text-[#65B9A3]">Good habits</h4>
    <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-1">
      <li>Rotate toys regularly — novelty keeps play exciting.</li>
      <li>Don't leave all toys out permanently; scarcity makes sessions more engaging.</li>
    </ul>
    <h4 class="font-semibold mt-3 mb-1 text-[#2d5a4e] dark:text-[#65B9A3]">Things to avoid</h4>
    <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-2">
      <li>
        <strong>Never play with your hands</strong> — what feels like play for a cat can
        be painful for you and raises infection risk.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Laser pointers</strong> — the concentrated beam can damage a cat's retina;
        and since the cat can never "catch" the prey, the nervous system is stimulated
        without reward, causing anxiety and apathy towards other toys.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-[#555] dark:text-[#848484]">
      <em>Good toy types:</em> natural material toys (safe if swallowed), interactive puzzle
      feeders (stimulate thinking, keep cats busy longer).
    </p>

    <div class="mt-5 h-55 w-70 bg-[#f5f0eb] dark:bg-[#454341] border border-dashed border-[#e8c4b8] rounded-lg flex items-center justify-center text-[#7a9070] text-sm italic">
      <img class="w-70" src="/cat-toys.png">
    </div>
    <p class="mt-2 text-xs text-[#7a9070] dark:text-[#A9AFA0]">
      Source:
      <a href="https://icatcare.org/advice/playing-with-your-cat/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
         class="underline hover:text-[#2d5a4e]">International Cat Care — Playing with your cat</a>
    </p>

    <h3 id="alone" class="font-bold text-xl text-[#774A33] dark:text-[#D49E84] mt-10 mb-2 scroll-mt-20">Alone time</h3>
    <p>Being left alone can be a significant source of stress. Help your cat adapt gradually:</p>
    <ol class="list-decimal pl-5 space-y-2 mt-2">
      <li>
        <strong>Start short</strong> — leave for 10–15 minutes, then an hour, increasing
        progressively. Avoid dramatic goodbyes; leave calmly and return without fuss.
      </li>
      <li>
        Establish a <strong>consistent routine</strong> for meals and interaction to give
        your cat a sense of stability.
      </li>
      <li>Pet shops sell toys specifically designed for periods of solitude.</li>
    </ol>
    <p class="mt-3">
      Provide a <strong>safe personal space</strong> — a cave-style bed where the cat can
      hide from noise. If the cat is inside it, never force them out or raise your voice near it.
    </p>
    <p class="mt-2 text-xs text-[#7a9070] dark:text-[#A9AFA0]">
      Source:
      <a href="https://icatcare.org/advice/cats-and-stress/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
         class="underline hover:text-[#2d5a4e]">International Cat Care — Cats and stress</a>
    </p>

    <h3 id="changes" class="font-bold text-xl text-[#774A33] dark:text-[#D49E84] mt-10 mb-2 scroll-mt-20">Introducing changes</h3>
    <p>
      Any change — new food, new litter, new environment — must be introduced
      <strong>gradually</strong>.
    </p>
    <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-2 mt-2">
      <li>
        <strong>New food:</strong> mix increasing amounts of the new food into the old over
        7–10 days. Watch for allergic reactions or intolerance.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>New litter:</strong> cats may refuse a new type due to smell, texture, or feel.
        Start with just one tray, keeping the other unchanged.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>

</ArticleLayout>